[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] In a programming language, an **evaluation strategy** is a set of rules for evaluating expressions.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] The notion of reduction strategy is distinct, although some authors conflate the two terms and the definition of each term is not widely agreed upon.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] A programming language's evaluation strategy is part of its high-level semantics.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] Some languages, such as PureScript, have variants with different evaluation strategies.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] Some declarative languages, such as Datalog, support multiple evaluation strategies.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] Just like in mathematics, evaluation is the process of finding the value corresponding to an expression.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] The calling convention consists of the low-level platform-specific details of parameter passing.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] To illustrate, executing a function call `f(a, b)` may first evaluate the arguments `a` and `b`, store the results in references or memory locations `ref_a` and `ref_b`, then evaluate the function's body with those references passed in.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] This gives the function the ability to look up the original argument values passed in through dereferencing the parameters (some languages use specific operators to perform this), to modify them via assignment as if they were local variables, and to return values via the references.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] This is the call-by-reference evaluation strategy.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] This is a table of evaluation strategies and representative languages by year introduced.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] The representative languages are listed in chronological order, starting with the language(s) that introduced the strategy and followed by prominent languages that use the strategy.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] While the order of operations defines the abstract syntax tree of the expression, the evaluation order defines the order in which expressions are evaluated.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] outputs `213` due to OCaml's right-to-left evaluation order.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] The evaluation order is mainly visible in code with side effects, but it also affects the performance of the code because a rigid order inhibits instruction scheduling.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] For this reason language standards such as C++ traditionally left the order unspecified, although languages such as Java and C# define the evaluation order as left-to-right and the C++17 standard has added constraints on the evaluation order.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] Common Lisp, Eiffel and Java evaluate function arguments left-to-right.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] Scheme requires the execution order to be the sequential execution of an unspecified permutation of the arguments.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] OCaml similarly leaves the order unspecified, but in practice evaluates arguments right-to-left due to the design of its abstract machine.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] A **non-strict evaluation order** is an evaluation order that is not strict, that is, a function may return a result before all of its arguments are fully evaluated.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] The prototypical example is **normal order evaluation**, which does not evaluate any of the arguments until they are needed in the body of the function.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] Normal order evaluation has the property that it terminates without error whenever any other evaluation order would have terminated without error.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] The name "normal order" comes from the lambda calculus, where normal order reduction will find a normal form if there is one (it is a "normalizing" reduction strategy).
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] Lazy evaluation is classified in this article as a binding technique rather than an evaluation order.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] But this distinction is not always followed and some authors define lazy evaluation as normal order evaluation or vice-versa, or confuse non-strictness with lazy evaluation.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] Conditional expressions similarly use non-strict evaluation - only one of the branches is evaluated.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] With normal order evaluation, expressions containing an expensive computation, an error, or an infinite loop will be ignored if not needed, allowing the specification of user-defined control flow constructs, a facility not available with applicative order evaluation.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] Normal order evaluation uses complex structures such as thunks for unevaluated expressions, compared to the call stack used in applicative order evaluation.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] Normal order evaluation has historically had a lack of usable debugging tools due to its complexity.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] In call by value (or pass by value), the evaluated value of the argument expression is bound to the corresponding variable in the function (frequently by copying the value into a new memory region).
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] If the function or procedure is able to assign values to its parameters, only its local variable is assigned—that is, anything passed into a function call is unchanged in the caller's scope when the function returns.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] Strictly speaking, under call by value, no operations performed by the called routine can be visible to the caller, other than as part of the return value.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] This implies a form of purely functional programming in the implementation semantics.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] However, the circumlocution "call by value where the value is a reference" has become common in some languages, for example, the Java community.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] Compared to traditional pass by value, the value which is passed is not a value as understood by the ordinary meaning of value, such as an integer that can be written as a literal, but an implementation-internal reference handle.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] Mutations to this reference handle are visible in the caller.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] Due to the visible mutation, this form of "call by value" is more properly referred to as call by sharing.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] In purely functional languages, values and data structures are immutable, so there is no possibility for a function to modify any of its arguments.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] As such, there is typically no semantic difference between passing by value and passing by reference or a pointer to the data structure, and implementations frequently use call by reference internally for the efficiency benefits.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] Nonetheless, these languages are typically described as call by value languages.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] Call by reference (or pass by reference) is an evaluation strategy where a parameter is bound to an implicit reference to the variable used as argument, rather than a copy of its value.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] This typically means that the function can modify (i.e., assign to) the variable used as argument—something that will be seen by its caller.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] Call by reference can therefore be used to provide an additional channel of communication between the called function and the calling function.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] Pass by reference can significantly improve performance: calling a function with a many-megabyte structure as an argument does not have to copy the large structure, only the reference to the structure (which is generally a machine word and only a few bytes).
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] However, a call-by-reference language makes it more difficult for a programmer to track the effects of a function call, and may introduce subtle bugs.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] Due to variation in syntax, the difference between call by reference (where the reference type is implicit) and call by sharing (where the reference type is explicit) is often unclear on first glance.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] A simple litmus test is if it's possible to write a traditional `swap(a, b)` function in the language.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] Therefore, Fortran's `inout` intent implements call-by-reference; any variable can be implicitly converted to a reference handle.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] where an explicit `Box` type must be used to introduce a handle.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] Java is call-by-sharing but not call-by-reference.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] Call by copy-restore—also known as "copy-in copy-out", "call by value result", "call by value return" (as termed in the Fortran community)—is a variation of call by reference.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] With call by copy-restore, the contents of the argument are copied to a new variable local to the call invocation.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] The function may then modify this variable, similarly to call by reference, but as the variable is local, the modifications are not visible outside of the call invocation during the call.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] When the function call returns, the updated contents of this variable are copied back to overwrite the original argument ("restored").
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] The semantics of call by copy-restore is similar in many cases to call by reference, but differs when two or more function arguments alias one another (i.e., point to the same variable in the caller's environment).
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] Under call by reference, writing to one argument will affect the other during the function's execution.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] Under call by copy-restore, writing to one argument will not affect the other during the function's execution, but at the end of the call, the values of the two arguments may differ, and it is unclear which argument is copied back first and therefore what value the caller's variable receives.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] For example, Ada specifies that the copy-out assignment for each `in out` or `out` parameter occurs in an arbitrary order.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] If the program returned 1 it would be copying right-to-left, and under call by reference semantics the program would return 3.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] When the reference is passed to the caller uninitialized (for example an `out` parameter in Ada as opposed to an `in out` parameter), this evaluation strategy may be called "call by result".
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] This strategy has gained attention in multiprocessing and remote procedure calls, as unlike call-by-reference it does not require frequent communication between threads of execution for variable access.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] Call by sharing (also known as "pass by sharing", "call by object", or "call by object-sharing") is an evaluation strategy that is intermediate between call by value and call by reference.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] Rather than every variable being exposed as a reference, only a specific class of values, termed "references", "boxed types", or "objects", have reference semantics, and it is the addresses of these pointers that are passed into the function.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] Like call by value, the value of the address passed is a copy, and direct assignment to the parameter of the function overwrites the copy and is not visible to the calling function.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] Like call by reference, mutating the target of the pointer is visible to the calling function.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] Mutations of a mutable object within the function are visible to the caller because the object is not copied or cloned—it is *shared*, hence the name "call by sharing".
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] The technique was first noted by Barbara Liskov in 1974 for the CLU language.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] The term "call by sharing" as used in this article is not in common use; the terminology is inconsistent across different sources.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] For example, in the Java community, they say that Java is call by value.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] For immutable objects, there is no real difference between call by sharing and call by value, except if object identity is visible in the language.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] The use of call by sharing with mutable objects is an alternative to input/output parameters: the parameter is not assigned to (the argument is not overwritten and object identity is not changed), but the object (argument) is mutated.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] outputs `[1]` because the `append` method modifies the object on which it is called.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] In contrast, assignments within a function are not noticeable to the caller.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] Some authors treat `&` as part of the syntax of calling `swap`.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] Under this view, C supports the call-by-reference parameter passing strategy.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] Other authors take a differing view that the presented implementation of `swap` in C is only a simulation of call-by-reference using pointers.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] Under this "simulation" view, mutable variables in C are not first-class (that is, l-values are not expressions), rather pointer types are.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] Because in this program, `swap` operates on pointers and cannot change the pointers themselves, but only the values the pointers point to, this view holds that C's main evaluation strategy is more similar to call-by-sharing.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] Semantically, this is equivalent to the C examples.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] As such, many authors consider call-by-address to be a unique parameter passing strategy distinct from call-by-value, call-by-reference, and call-by-sharing.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] In logic programming, the evaluation of an expression may simply correspond to the unification of the terms involved combined with the application of some form of resolution.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] Unification must be classified as a strict binding strategy because it is fully performed.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] However, unification can also be performed on unbounded variables, so calls may not necessarily commit to final values for all its variables.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] Call by name is an evaluation strategy where the arguments to a function are not evaluated before the function is called—rather, they are substituted directly into the function body (using capture-avoiding substitution) and then left to be evaluated whenever they appear in the function.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] If an argument is not used in the function body, the argument is never evaluated; if it is used several times, it is re-evaluated each time it appears.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] Call-by-name evaluation is occasionally preferable to call-by-value evaluation.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] If a function's argument is not used in the function, call by name will save time by not evaluating the argument, whereas call by value will evaluate it regardless.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] If the argument is a non-terminating computation, the advantage is enormous.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] However, when the function argument is used, call by name is often slower, requiring a mechanism such as a thunk.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] .NET languages can simulate call by name using delegates or `Expression<T>` parameters.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] The latter results in an abstract syntax tree being given to the function.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] Eiffel provides agents, which represent an operation to be evaluated when needed.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] Java programs can accomplish similar lazy evaluation using lambda expressions and the `java.util.function.Supplier<T>` interface.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] Call by need is a memoized variant of call by name, where, if the function argument is evaluated, that value is stored for subsequent use.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] If the argument is pure (i.e., free of side effects), this produces the same results as call by name, saving the cost of recomputing the argument.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] Haskell is a well-known language that uses call-by-need evaluation.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] Because evaluation of expressions may happen arbitrarily far into a computation, Haskell supports only side effects (such as mutation) via the use of monads.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] This eliminates any unexpected behavior from variables whose values change prior to their delayed evaluation.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] In R's implementation of call by need, all arguments are passed, meaning that R allows arbitrary side effects.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] Lazy evaluation is the most common implementation of call-by-need semantics, but variations like optimistic evaluation exist. .NET languages implement call by need using the type `Lazy<T>`.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] Graph reduction is an efficient implementation of lazy evaluation.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] Call by macro expansion is similar to call by name, but uses textual substitution rather than capture-avoiding substitution.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] Macro substitution may therefore result in variable capture, leading to mistakes and undesired behavior.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] Hygienic macros avoid this problem by checking for and replacing shadowed variables that are not parameters.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] "Call by future", also known as "parallel call by name" or "lenient evaluation", is a concurrent evaluation strategy combining non-strict semantics with eager evaluation.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] The method requires fine-grained dynamic scheduling and synchronization but is suitable for massively parallel machines.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] The strategy creates a future (promise) for the function's body and each of its arguments.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] These futures are computed concurrently with the flow of the rest of the program.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] When a future A requires the value of another future B that has not yet been computed, future A blocks until future B finishes computing and has a value.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] If future B has already finished computing the value is returned immediately.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] Conditionals block until their condition is evaluated, and lambdas do not create futures until they are fully applied.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] If implemented with processes or threads, creating a future will spawn one or more new processes or threads (for the promises), accessing the value will synchronize these with the main thread, and terminating the computation of the future corresponds to killing the promises computing its value.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] If implemented with a coroutine, as in .NET async/await, creating a future calls a coroutine (an async function), which may yield to the caller, and in turn be yielded back to when the value is used, cooperatively multitasking.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] The strategy is non-deterministic, as the evaluation can occur at any time between creation of the future (i.e., when the expression is given) and use of the future's value.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] The strategy is non-strict because the function body may return a value before the arguments are evaluated.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] However, in most implementations, execution may still get stuck evaluating an unneeded argument.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] may either have `g` finish before `f`, and output 1, or may result in an error due to evaluating `1/0`.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] Call-by-future is similar to call by need in that values are computed only once.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] With careful handling of errors and nontermination, in particular terminating futures partway through if it is determined they will not be needed, call-by-future also has the same termination properties as call-by-need evaluation.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] However, call-by-future may perform unnecessary speculative work compared to call-by-need, such as deeply evaluating a lazy data structure.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] This can be avoided by using lazy futures that do not start computation until it is certain the value is needed.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] Optimistic evaluation is a call-by-need variant where the function's argument is partly evaluated in a call-by-value style for some amount of time (which may be adjusted at runtime).
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] After that time has passed, evaluation is aborted and the function is applied using call by need.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/evaluation-strategy] This approach avoids some of call-by-need's runtime expenses while retaining desired termination characteristics.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] In computer science, **futures**, **promises**, **delays**, and **deferreds** are constructs used for synchronizing program execution in some concurrent programming languages.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] Each is an object that acts as a proxy for a result that is initially unknown, usually because the computation of its value is not yet complete.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] The term *promise* was proposed in 1976 by Daniel P.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] Friedman and David Wise, and Peter Hibbard called it *eventual*.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] A somewhat similar concept *future* was introduced in 1977 in a paper by Henry Baker and Carl Hewitt.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] The terms *future*, *promise*, *delay*, and *deferred* are often used interchangeably, although there can be some differences in usage between *future* and *promise*.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] Specifically, when usage is distinguished, a future is a *read-only* placeholder view of a variable, while a promise is a writable, single assignment container which sets the value of the future.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] Notably, a future may be defined without specifying which specific promise will set its value, and different possible promises may set the value of a given future, though this can be done only once for a given future.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] In other cases a future and a promise are created together and associated with each other: the future is the value, the promise is the function that sets the value – essentially the return value (future) of an asynchronous function (promise).
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] Setting the value of a future is also called *resolving*, *fulfilling*, or *binding* it.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] Futures and promises originated in functional programming and related paradigms (such as logic programming) to decouple a value (a future) from how it was computed (a promise), allowing the computation to be done more flexibly, notably by parallelizing it.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] Later, it found use in distributed computing, in reducing the latency from communication round trips.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] Later still, it gained more use by allowing writing asynchronous programs in direct style, rather than in continuation-passing style.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] Use of futures may be *implicit* (any use of the future automatically obtains its value, as if it were an ordinary reference) or *explicit* (the user must call a function to obtain the value, such as the `get` method of `java.util.concurrent.Future`in Java).
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] Obtaining the value of an explicit future can be called *stinging* or *forcing*.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] Explicit futures can be implemented as a library, whereas implicit futures are usually implemented as part of the language.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] The original Baker and Hewitt paper described implicit futures, which are naturally supported in the actor model of computation and pure object-oriented programming languages like Smalltalk.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] The Friedman and Wise paper described only explicit futures, probably reflecting the difficulty of efficiently implementing implicit futures on stock hardware.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] The difficulty is that stock hardware does not deal with futures for primitive data types like integers.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] For example, an add instruction does not know how to deal with `3 + *future* factorial(100000)`.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] In pure actor or object languages this problem can be solved by sending `*future* factorial(100000)` the message `+[3]`, which asks the future to add `3` to itself and return the result.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] Note that the message passing approach works regardless of when `factorial(100000)` finishes computation and that no stinging/forcing is needed.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] The use of futures can dramatically reduce latency in distributed systems.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] For instance, futures enable *promise pipelining*, as implemented in the languages E and Joule, which was also called *call-stream* in the language Argus.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] Each statement needs a message to be sent and a reply received before the next statement can proceed.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] Suppose, for example, that `x`, `y`, `t1`, and `t2` are all located on the same remote machine.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] In this case, two complete network round-trips to that machine must take place before the third statement can begin to execute.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] The third statement will then cause yet another round-trip to the same remote machine.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] The syntax used here is that of the language E, where `x <- a()` means to send the message `a()` asynchronously to `x`.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] All three variables are immediately assigned futures for their results, and execution proceeds to subsequent statements.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] Later attempts to resolve the value of `t3` may cause a delay; however, pipelining can reduce the number of round-trips needed.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] If, as in the prior example, `x`, `y`, `t1`, and `t2` are all located on the same remote machine, a pipelined implementation can compute `t3` with one round-trip instead of three.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] Because all three messages are destined for objects which are on the same remote machine, only one request need be sent and only one response need be received containing the result.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] The send `t1 <- c(t2)` would not block even if `t1` and `t2` were on different machines to each other, or to `x` or `y`.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] Promise pipelining should be distinguished from parallel asynchronous message passing.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] The relative latency advantage of pipelining becomes even greater in more complicated situations involving many messages.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] Promise pipelining also should not be confused with pipelined message processing in actor systems, where it is possible for an actor to specify and begin executing a behaviour for the next message before having completed processing of the current message.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] Support for read-only views is consistent with the principle of least privilege, since it enables the ability to set the value to be restricted to subjects that need to set it.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] In a system that also supports pipelining, the sender of an asynchronous message (with result) receives the read-only promise for the result, and the target of the message receives the resolver.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] Some languages, such as Alice ML, define futures that are associated with a specific thread that computes the future's value.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] This computation can start either eagerly when the future is created, or lazily when its value is first needed.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] A lazy future is similar to a thunk, in the sense of a delayed computation.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] Alice ML also supports futures that can be resolved by any thread, and calls these *promises*.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] This use of *promise* is different from its use in E as described above.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] In Alice, a promise is not a read-only view, and promise pipelining is unsupported.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] Instead, pipelining naturally happens for futures, including ones associated with promises.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] If the value of a future is accessed asynchronously, for example by sending a message to it, or by explicitly waiting for it using a construct such as `when` in E, then there is no difficulty in delaying until the future is resolved before the message can be received or the wait completes.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] This is the only case to be considered in purely asynchronous systems such as pure actor languages.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] However, in some systems it may also be possible to attempt to *immediately* or *synchronously* access a future's value.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] As an example of the first possibility, in C++11, a thread that needs the value of a future can block until it is available by calling the `wait()` or `get()` member functions.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] A timeout can also be specified on the wait using the `wait_for()` or `wait_until()` member functions to avoid indefinite blocking.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] If the future arose from a call to `std::async` then a blocking wait (without a timeout) may cause synchronous invocation of the function to compute the result on the waiting thread.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] An *I-var* (as in the language Id) is a future with blocking semantics as defined above.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] An *I-structure* is a data structure containing I-vars.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] A related synchronization construct that can be set multiple times with different values is called an *M-var*.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] M-vars support atomic operations to *take* or *put* the current value, where taking the value also sets the M-var back to its initial *empty* state.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] A *concurrent logic variable* is similar to a future, but is updated by unification, in the same way as *logic variables* in logic programming.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] Thus it can be bound more than once to unifiable values, but cannot be set back to an empty or unresolved state.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] The dataflow variables of Oz act as concurrent logic variables, and also have blocking semantics as mentioned above.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] A *concurrent constraint variable* is a generalization of concurrent logic variables to support constraint logic programming: the constraint may be *narrowed* multiple times, indicating smaller sets of possible values.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] Typically there is a way to specify a thunk that should run whenever the constraint is narrowed further; this is needed to support *constraint propagation*.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] Eager thread-specific futures can be straightforwardly implemented in non-thread-specific futures, by creating a thread to calculate the value at the same time as creating the future.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] In this case it is desirable to return a read-only view to the client, so that only the newly created thread is able to resolve this future.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] To implement implicit lazy thread-specific futures (as provided by Alice ML, for example) in terms in non-thread-specific futures, needs a mechanism to determine when the future's value is first needed (for example, the `WaitNeeded` construct in Oz).
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] If all values are objects, then the ability to implement transparent forwarding objects is sufficient, since the first message sent to the forwarder indicates that the future's value is needed.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] Non-thread-specific futures can be implemented in thread-specific futures, assuming that the system supports message passing, by having the resolving thread send a message to the future's own thread.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] However, this can be viewed as unneeded complexity.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] In programming languages based on threads, the most expressive approach seems to be to provide a mix of non-thread-specific futures, read-only views, and either a *WaitNeeded* construct, or support for transparent forwarding.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] The evaluation strategy of futures, which may be termed *call by future*, is non-deterministic: the value of a future will be evaluated at some time between when the future is created and when its value is used, but the precise time is not determined beforehand and can change from run to run.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] The computation can start as soon as the future is created (eager evaluation) or only when the value is actually needed (lazy evaluation), and may be suspended part-way through, or executed in one run.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] Once the value of a future is assigned, it is not recomputed on future accesses; this is like the memoization used in call by need.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] A **lazy future** is a future that deterministically has lazy evaluation semantics: the computation of the future's value starts when the value is first needed, as in call by need.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] Lazy futures are of use in languages which evaluation strategy is by default not lazy.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] For example, in C++11 such lazy futures can be created by passing the `std::launch::deferred` launch policy to `std::async`, along with the function to compute the value.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] If it does not already have a response, then *R* is stored in the queue of requests inside the *F*.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] However, some futures can deal with requests in special ways to provide greater parallelism.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] For example, the expression `1 + future factorial(n)` can create a new future that will behave like the number `1+factorial(n)`.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] suspends until the future for `factorial(n)` has responded to the request asking if `m` is greater than itself.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] The *future* and/or *promise* constructs were first implemented in programming languages such as MultiLisp and Act 1.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] The use of logic variables for communication in concurrent logic programming languages was quite similar to futures.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] These began in *Prolog with Freeze* and *IC Prolog*, and became a true concurrency primitive with Relational Language, Concurrent Prolog, guarded Horn clauses (GHC), Parlog, Strand, Vulcan, Janus, Oz-Mozart, Flow Java, and Alice ML.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] The single-assignment *I-var* from dataflow programming languages, originating in Id and included in Reppy's *Concurrent ML*, is much like the concurrent logic variable.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] The promise pipelining technique (using futures to overcome latency) was invented by Barbara Liskov and Liuba Shrira in 1988, and independently by Mark S.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] Miller, Dean Tribble and Rob Jellinghaus in the context of Project Xanadu circa 1989.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] The term *promise* was coined by Liskov and Shrira, although they referred to the pipelining mechanism by the name *call-stream*, which is now rarely used.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] It seems that promises and call-streams were never implemented in any public release of Argus, the programming language used in the Liskov and Shrira paper.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] The Xanadu implementation of promise pipelining only became publicly available with the release of the source code for Udanax Gold in 1999, and was never explained in any published document.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] The later implementations in Joule and E support fully first-class promises and resolvers.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] Several early actor languages, including the Act series, supported both parallel message passing and pipelined message processing, but not promise pipelining.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] After 2000, a major revival of interest in futures and promises occurred, due to their use in responsiveness of user interfaces, and in web development, due to the request–response model of message-passing.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] This has subsequently been adopted by other languages, notably Dart (2014), Python (2015), Hack (HHVM), and drafts of ECMAScript 7 (JavaScript), Scala, and C++ (2011).
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] Some programming languages are supporting futures, promises, concurrent logic variables, dataflow variables, or I-vars, either by direct language support or in the standard library.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] Futures can be implemented in coroutines or generators, resulting in the same evaluation strategy (e.g., cooperative multitasking or lazy evaluation).
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] Futures can easily be implemented in channels: a future is a one-element channel, and a promise is a process that sends to the channel, fulfilling the future.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] This allows futures to be implemented in concurrent programming languages with support for channels, such as CSP and Go.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/futures-and-promises] The resulting futures are explicit, as they must be accessed by reading from the channel, rather than only evaluation.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] In programming language theory, **lazy evaluation**, or **call-by-need**, is an evaluation strategy which delays the evaluation of an expression until its value is needed (non-strict evaluation) and which avoids repeated evaluations (by the use of sharing).
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] Lazy evaluation is often combined with memoization, as described in Jon Bentley's *Writing Efficient Programs*.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] If so, the stored result is simply returned.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] If not, the function is evaluated, and another entry is added to the lookup table for reuse.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] Lazy evaluation is difficult to combine with imperative features such as exception handling and input/output, because the order of operations becomes indeterminate.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] The opposite of lazy evaluation is eager evaluation, sometimes known as strict evaluation.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] Eager evaluation is the evaluation strategy employed in most programming languages.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] Lazy evaluation was introduced for lambda calculus by Christopher Wadsworth.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] For programming languages, it was independently introduced by Peter Henderson and James H.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] Delayed evaluation is used particularly in functional programming languages.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] When using delayed evaluation, an expression is not evaluated as soon as it gets bound to a variable, but when the evaluator is forced to produce the expression's value.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] Lazy evaluation is fundamental in big data frameworks such as Apache Spark, where computations on distributed datasets are delayed until results are explicitly needed, allowing for execution optimizations and reduction of unnecessary processing.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] Lazy evaluation allows control structures to be defined normally, and not as primitives or compile-time techniques.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] These have the usual semantics, i.e., `ifThenElse a b c` evaluates (a), then if and only if (a) evaluates to true does it evaluate (b), otherwise it evaluates (c).
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] That is, exactly one of (b) or (c) will be evaluated.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] Similarly, for `EasilyComputed || LotsOfWork`, if the easy part gives **True** the lots of work expression could be avoided.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] Finally, when evaluating `SafeToTry && Expression`, if *SafeToTry* is **false** there will be no attempt at evaluating the *Expression*.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] Conversely, in an eager language the above definition for `ifThenElse a b c` would evaluate (a), (b), and (c) regardless of the value of (a).
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] This is not the desired behavior, as (b) or (c) may have side effects, take a long time to compute, or throw errors.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] It is usually possible to introduce user-defined lazy control structures in eager languages as functions, though they may depart from the language's syntax for eager evaluation: Often the involved code bodies need to be wrapped in a function value, so that they are executed only when called.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] Delayed evaluation has the advantage of being able to create calculable infinite lists without infinite loops or size matters interfering in computation.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] The actual values are only computed when needed.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] For example, one could create a function that creates an infinite list (often called a *stream*) of Fibonacci numbers.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] The calculation of the *n*-th Fibonacci number would be merely the extraction of that element from the infinite list, forcing the evaluation of only the first n members of the list.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] In the function numberFromInfiniteList, the value of infinity is an infinite range, but until an actual value (or more specifically, a specific value at a certain index) is needed, the list is not evaluated, and even then, it is only evaluated as needed (i.e., only to the desired index).
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] Provided the programmer is careful, the program completes normally.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] In Haskell syntax, "`:`" prepends an element to a list, `tail` returns a list without its first element, and `zipWith` uses a specified function (in this case addition) to combine corresponding elements of two lists to produce a third.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] In computer windowing systems, the painting of information to the screen is driven by *expose events* which drive the display code at the last possible moment.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] By doing this, windowing systems avoid computing unnecessary display content updates.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] Another example of laziness in modern computer systems is copy-on-write page allocation or demand paging, where memory is allocated only when a value stored in that memory is changed.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] Laziness can be useful for high performance scenarios.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] An example is the Unix mmap function, which provides *demand driven* loading of pages from disk, so that only those pages actually touched are loaded into memory, and unneeded memory is not allocated.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] MATLAB implements *copy on edit*, where arrays which are copied have their actual memory storage replicated only when their content is changed, possibly leading to an *out of memory* error when updating an element afterwards instead of during the copy operation.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] The number of beta reductions to reduce a lambda term with call-by-need is not larger than the number needed by call-by-value or call-by-name reduction.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] Call-by-need embodies two optimizations - never repeat work (similar to call-by-value), and never perform unnecessary work (similar to call-by-name).
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] Lazy evaluation can also lead to reduction in memory footprint, since values are created when needed.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] In practice, lazy evaluation may cause significant performance issues compared to eager evaluation.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] For example, on modern computer architectures, delaying a computation and performing it later is slower than performing it immediately .
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] This can be alleviated through strictness analysis.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] Lazy evaluation can also introduce memory leaks due to unevaluated expressions.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] Some programming languages delay evaluation of expressions by default, and some others provide functions or special syntax to delay evaluation.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] In KRC, Miranda, and Haskell, evaluation of function arguments is delayed by default.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] In many other languages, evaluation can be delayed by explicitly suspending the computation using special syntax (as with Scheme's "`delay`" and "`force`" and OCaml's "`lazy`" and "`Lazy.force`") or, more generally, by wrapping the expression in a thunk.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] In lazy programming languages such as Haskell, although the default is to evaluate expressions only when they are demanded, it is possible in some cases to make code more eager—or conversely, to make it more lazy again after it has been made more eager.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] This can be done by explicitly coding something which forces evaluation (which may make the code more eager) or avoiding such code (which may make the code more lazy).
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] *Strict* evaluation usually implies eagerness, but they are technically different concepts.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] However, there is an optimisation implemented in some compilers called strictness analysis, which, in some cases, allows the compiler to infer that a value will always be used.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] In such cases, this may render the programmer's choice of whether to force that particular value or not, irrelevant, because strictness analysis will force strict evaluation.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] In Haskell, marking constructor fields strict means that their values will always be demanded immediately.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] The `seq` function can also be used to demand a value immediately and then pass it on, which is useful if a constructor field should generally be lazy.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] However, neither of these techniques implements *recursive* strictness—for that, a function called `deepSeq` was invented.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] Also, pattern matching in Haskell 98 is strict by default, so the `~` qualifier has to be used to make it lazy.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] In C++, the `std::ranges` library uses lazy range adaptors.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] In Java, lazy evaluation can be done by using objects that have a method to evaluate them when the value is needed.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] The body of this method must contain the code required to perform this evaluation.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] Since the introduction of lambda expressions in Java SE8, Java has supported a compact notation for this.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] The `Lazy` interface with its `eval()` method is equivalent to the `Supplier` interface with its `get()` method in the `java.util.function` library.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] Each class that implements the `Lazy` interface must provide an `eval` method, and instances of the class may carry whatever values the method needs to accomplish lazy evaluation.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] In the above, the variable a initially refers to a lazy integer object created by the lambda expression `() -> 1`.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] Evaluating this lambda expression is similar to constructing a new instance of an anonymous class that implements `Lazy<Integer>` with an eval method returning 1.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] Each iteration of the loop links a to a new object created by evaluating the lambda expression inside the loop.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] Each of these objects holds a reference to another lazy object, b, and has an eval method that calls `b.eval()` twice and returns the sum.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] The variable b is needed here to meet Java's requirement that variables referenced from within a lambda expression be effectively final.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] This is an inefficient program because this implementation of lazy integers does not memoize the result of previous calls to eval.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] It also involves considerable autoboxing and unboxing.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] What may not be obvious is that, at the end of the loop, the program has constructed a linked list of 11 objects and that all of the actual additions involved in computing the result are done in response to the call to `a.eval()` on the final line of code.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] This call recursively traverses the list to perform the necessary additions.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] This allows the previous example to be rewritten to be far more efficient.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] Java's lambda expressions are just syntactic sugar.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] In JavaScript, lazy evaluation can be simulated by using a generator.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] You can run this example yourself by going to the Kotlin Playground.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] To verify that the program lazily loaded `isThePizzaReady` instead of initializing it beforehand as true we need to check the output of the program.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] As we can see when the program reads from `isThePizzaReady` it prints out a statement we put inside the lazy code block on line 4.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] The statement on line 4 does not execute more than once.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] In Python 2.x the `range()` function computes a list of integers.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] In Python 3.x the `range()` function returns a generator which computes elements of the list on demand.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] This change to lazy evaluation saves execution time for large ranges which may never be fully referenced and memory usage for large ranges where only one or a few elements are needed at any time.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] In Python 2.x is possible to use a function called `xrange()` which returns an object that generates the numbers in the range on demand.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] The advantage of `xrange` is that generated object will always take the same amount of memory.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] From version 2.2 forward, Python manifests lazy evaluation by implementing iterators (lazy sequences) unlike tuple or list sequences.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] , the first element '0' is printed when need arises.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] In the .NET framework, it is possible to do lazy evaluation using the class `System.Lazy<T>`.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] The class can be easily exploited in F# using the `lazy` keyword, while the `force` method will force the evaluation.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] There are also specialized collections like `Microsoft.FSharp.Collections.Seq` that provide built-in support for lazy evaluation.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/lazy-evaluation] In C# and VB.NET, the class `System.Lazy<T>` is directly used.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] In computing, **memoization** or **memoisation** is an optimization technique used primarily to speed up computer programs.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] It works by storing the results of expensive calls to pure functions, so that these results can be returned quickly should the same inputs occur again.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] It is a type of caching, normally implemented using a hash table, and a typical example of a space–time tradeoff, where the runtime of a program is reduced by increasing its memory usage.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] Memoization can be implemented in any programming language, though some languages have built-in support that make it easy for the programmer to memoize a function, and others memoize certain functions by default.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] Memoization has also been used in other contexts (and for purposes other than speed gains), such as in simple mutually recursive descent parsing.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] In the context of some logic programming languages, memoization is also known as tabling.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] The term *memoization* was coined by Donald Michie in 1968 and is derived from the Latin word *memorandum* ('to be remembered'), usually truncated as *memo* in American English, and thus carries the meaning of 'turning [the results of] a function into something to be remembered'.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] While *memoization* might be confused with *memorization* (because they are etymological cognates), *memoization* has a specialized meaning in computing.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] A memoized function, when called with a given set of inputs for the first time, stores the inputs along with the computed results.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] Upon subsequent calls with remembered inputs, the function returns the remembered results rather than recomputing them, thus eliminating the cost of a recomputation.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] The set of remembered associations may be a fixed-size set controlled by a replacement algorithm or a fixed set, depending on the nature of the function and its use.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] A function can only be memoized if it is referentially transparent; that is, only if calling the function has exactly the same effect as replacing that function call with its return value.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] (Special case exceptions to this restriction exist, however.) While related to lookup tables, since memoization often uses such tables in its implementation, memoization populates its cache of results transparently on the fly, rather than needing them to be supplied in advance.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] Memoized functions are optimized for *speed* in exchange for a higher use of computer memory *space*.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] The time/space "cost" of algorithms has a specific name in computing: *computational complexity*.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] All functions have a computational complexity in *time* (i.e. they take time to execute) and in *space*.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] Although a space–time tradeoff occurs (i.e., space used is speed gained), this differs from some other optimizations that involve time-space trade-off, such as strength reduction, in that memoization is a run-time rather than compile-time optimization.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] For every integer *n* such that `*n* ≥ 0`, the final result of the function `factorial` is invariant; if invoked as `*x* = factorial(3)`, the result is such that *x* will *always* be assigned the value 6.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] The non-memoized implementation above, given the nature of the recursive algorithm involved, would require *n + 1* invocations of `factorial` to arrive at a result, and each of these invocations, in turn, has an associated cost in the time it takes the function to return the value computed.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] The cost to set up the recursive call stack frame.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] The cost to multiply the result of the recursive call to `factorial` by *n*.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] The cost to store the return result so that it may be used by the calling context.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] In a non-memoized implementation, *every* top-level call to `factorial` includes the cumulative cost of steps 2 through 6 proportional to the initial value of *n*.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] If it is then called with a number greater than 5, such as 7, only 2 recursive calls will be made (7 and 6), and the value for 5! will have been stored from the previous call.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] In this way, memoization allows a function to become more time-efficient the more often it is called, thus resulting in eventual overall speed-up.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] An extreme example of memoization is the Singleton pattern, specifically the implementation of its getter — a function that creates an object upon the first invocation, caches the instance, and returns the same object on all subsequent invocations.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] Memoization is heavily used in compilers for functional programming languages, which often use call by name evaluation strategy.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] To avoid overhead with calculating argument values, compilers for these languages heavily use auxiliary functions called thunks to compute the argument values, and memoize these functions to avoid repeated calculations.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] While memoization may be added to functions *internally* and *explicitly* by a computer programmer in much the same way the above memoized version of `factorial` is implemented, referentially transparent functions may also be automatically memoized *externally*.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] The techniques employed by Peter Norvig have application not only in Common Lisp (the language in which his paper demonstrated automatic memoization), but also in various other programming languages.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] Applications of automatic memoization have also been formally explored in the study of term rewriting and artificial intelligence.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] In programming languages where functions are first-class objects (such as Lua, Python, or Perl), automatic memoization can be implemented by replacing (at run-time) a function with its calculated value once a value has been calculated for a given set of parameters.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] The function that does this value-for-function-object replacement can generically wrap any referentially transparent function.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] In order to call an automatically memoized version of `factorial` using the above strategy, rather than calling `factorial` directly, code invokes `memoized-call(factorial)(*n*)`.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] Each such call first checks to see if a holder array has been allocated to store results, and if not, attaches that array.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] If no entry exists at the position `values[arguments]` (where `arguments` are used as the key of the associative array), a *real* call is made to `factorial` with the supplied arguments.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] Finally, the entry in the array at the key position is returned to the caller.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] The above strategy requires *explicit* wrapping at each call to a function that is to be memoized.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] In those languages that allow closures, memoization can be effected *implicitly* via a functor factory that returns a wrapped memoized function object in a decorator pattern.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] The above example assumes that the function `factorial` has already been defined *before* the call to `construct-memoized-functor` is made.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] From this point forward, `memfact(*n*)` is called whenever the factorial of *n* is desired.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] When a top-down parser tries to parse an ambiguous input with respect to an ambiguous context-free grammar (CFG), it may need an exponential number of steps (with respect to the length of the input) to try all alternatives of the CFG in order to produce all possible parse trees.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] This eventually would require exponential memory space.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] The basic idea in Norvig's approach is that when a parser is applied to the input, the result is stored in a memotable for subsequent reuse if the same parser is ever reapplied to the same input.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] Richard Frost and Barbara Szydlowski also used memoization to reduce the exponential time complexity of parser combinators, describing the result as a memoizing purely functional top-down backtracking language processor.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] Frost showed that basic memoized parser combinators can be used as building blocks to construct complex parsers as executable specifications of CFGs.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] Memoization was again explored in the context of parsing in 1995 by Mark Johnson and Jochen Dörre.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] In 2002, it was examined in considerable depth by Bryan Ford in the form called packrat parsing.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] In 2007, Frost, Hafiz and Callaghan described a top-down parsing algorithm that uses memoization for refraining redundant computations to accommodate any form of ambiguous CFG in polynomial time (Θ(n4) for left-recursive grammars and Θ(n3) for non left-recursive grammars).
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] Their top-down parsing algorithm also requires polynomial space for potentially exponential ambiguous parse trees by 'compact representation' and 'local ambiguities grouping'.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] Their compact representation is comparable with Tomita's compact representation of bottom-up parsing.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] Frost, Hafiz and Callaghan also described the implementation of the algorithm in PADL’08 as a set of higher-order functions (called parser combinators) in Haskell, which enables the construction of directly executable specifications of CFGs as language processors.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] The importance of their polynomial algorithm's power to accommodate ‘any form of ambiguous CFG’ with top-down parsing is vital with respect to the syntax and semantics analysis during natural language processing.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] The X-SAIGA site has more about the algorithm and implementation details.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] While Norvig increased the *power* of the parser through memoization, the augmented parser was still as time complex as Earley's algorithm, which demonstrates a case of the use of memoization for something other than speed optimization.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] Johnson and Dörre demonstrate another such non-speed related application of memoization: the use of memoization to delay linguistic constraint resolution to a point in a parse where sufficient information has been accumulated to resolve those constraints.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] By contrast, in the speed optimization application of memoization, Ford demonstrated that memoization could guarantee that parsing expression grammars could parse in linear time even those languages that resulted in worst-case backtracking behavior.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] The key concept here is inherent in the phrase **again descends into *X***.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] The process of looking forward, failing, backing up, and then retrying the next alternative is known in parsing as backtracking, and it is primarily backtracking that presents opportunities for memoization in parsing.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] Let the return value of the function `RuleAcceptsSomeInput` be the length of the input accepted by `Rule`, or 0 if that rule does not accept any input at that offset in the string.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] In the above example, one or *many* descents into *X* may occur, allowing for strings such as *xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxbd*.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] In fact, there may be *any number* of *x*'s before the *b*.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] While the call to S must recursively descend into X as many times as there are *x*'s, *B* will never have to descend into X at all, since the return value of `RuleAcceptsSomeInput(*X*, 0, *xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxbd*)` will be 16 (in this particular case).
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] For the same reason, memoized parser algorithms that generate calls to external code (sometimes called a semantic action routine) when a rule matches must use some scheme to ensure that such rules are invoked in a predictable order.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/memoization] This effect can be mitigated by explicit selection of those rules the parser will memoize.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/thunk] In computer programming, a **thunk** is a subroutine used to inject a calculation into another subroutine.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/thunk] Thunks are primarily used to delay a calculation until its result is needed, or to insert operations at the beginning or end of the other subroutine.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/thunk] They have many other applications in compiler code generation and modular programming.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/thunk] The term originated as a whimsical irregular form of the verb *think*.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/thunk] It refers to the original use of thunks in ALGOL 60 compilers, which required special analysis (thought) to determine what type of routine to generate.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/thunk] The early years of compiler research saw broad experimentation with different evaluation strategies.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/thunk] A key question was how to compile a subroutine call if the arguments can be arbitrary mathematical expressions rather than constants.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/thunk] One approach, known as "call by value", calculates all of the arguments before the call and then passes the resulting values to the subroutine.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/thunk] In the rival "call by name" approach, the subroutine receives the unevaluated argument expression and must evaluate it.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/thunk] A simple implementation of "call by name" might substitute the code of an argument expression for each appearance of the corresponding parameter in the subroutine, but this can produce multiple versions of the subroutine and multiple copies of the expression code.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/thunk] As an improvement, the compiler can generate a helper subroutine, called a *thunk*, that calculates the value of the argument.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/thunk] The address and environment of this helper subroutine are then passed to the original subroutine in place of the original argument, where it can be called as many times as needed.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/thunk] Peter Ingerman first described thunks in reference to the ALGOL 60 programming language, which supports call-by-name evaluation.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/thunk] Although the software industry largely standardized on call-by-value and call-by-reference evaluation, active study of call-by-name continued in the functional programming community.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/thunk] This research produced a series of lazy evaluation programming languages in which some variant of call-by-name is the standard evaluation strategy.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/thunk] Compilers for these languages, such as the Glasgow Haskell Compiler, have relied heavily on thunks, with the added feature that the thunks save their initial result so that they can avoid recalculating it; this is known as memoization or call-by-need.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/thunk] Functional programming languages have also allowed programmers to explicitly generate thunks.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/thunk] This is done in source code by wrapping an argument expression in an anonymous function that has no parameters of its own.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/thunk] This prevents the expression from being evaluated until a receiving function calls the anonymous function, thereby achieving the same effect as call-by-name.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/thunk] The adoption of anonymous functions into other programming languages has made this capability widely available.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/thunk] Thunks are useful in object-oriented programming platforms that allow a class to inherit multiple interfaces, leading to situations where the same method might be called via any of several interfaces.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/thunk] The following code illustrates such a situation in C++.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/thunk] In this example, the code generated for each of the classes A, B and C will include a dispatch table that can be used to call `Access` on an object of that type, via a reference that has the same type.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/thunk] Class C will have an additional dispatch table, used to call `Access` on an object of type C via a reference of type B.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/thunk] The expression `b->Access()` will use B's own dispatch table or the additional C table, depending on the type of object b refers to.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/thunk] If it refers to an object of type C, the compiler must ensure that C's `Access` implementation receives an instance address for the entire C object, rather than the inherited B part of that object.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/thunk] As a direct approach to this pointer adjustment problem, the compiler can include an integer offset in each dispatch table entry.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/thunk] This offset is the difference between the reference's address and the address required by the method implementation.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/thunk] The code generated for each call through these dispatch tables must then retrieve the offset and use it to adjust the instance address before calling the method.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/thunk] The solution just described has problems similar to the naïve implementation of call-by-name described earlier: the compiler generates several copies of code to calculate an argument (the instance address), while also increasing the dispatch table sizes to hold the offsets.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/thunk] As an alternative, the compiler can generate an *adjustor thunk* along with C's implementation of `Access` that adjusts the instance address by the required amount and then calls the method.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/thunk] The thunk can appear in C's dispatch table for B, thereby eliminating the need for callers to adjust the address themselves.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/thunk] Thunks have been widely used to provide interoperability between software modules whose routines cannot call each other directly.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/thunk] This may occur because the routines have different calling conventions, run in different CPU modes or address spaces, or at least one runs in a virtual machine.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/thunk] A compiler (or other tool) can solve this problem by generating a thunk that automates the additional steps needed to call the target routine, whether that is transforming arguments, copying them to another location, or switching the CPU mode.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/thunk] A successful thunk minimizes the extra work the caller must do compared to a normal call.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/thunk] Much of the literature on interoperability thunks relates to various Wintel platforms, including MS-DOS, OS/2, Windows and .NET, and to the transition from 16-bit to 32-bit memory addressing.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/thunk] As customers have migrated from one platform to another, thunks have been essential to support legacy software written for the older platforms.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/thunk] UEFI CSM is another example to do thunk for legacy boot loaders.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/thunk] The transition from 32-bit to 64-bit code on x86 also uses a form of thunking (WoW64).
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/thunk] However, because the x86-64 address space is larger than the one available to 32-bit code, the old "generic thunk" mechanism could not be used to call 64-bit code from 32-bit code.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/thunk] The only case of 32-bit code calling 64-bit code is in the WoW64's thunking of Windows APIs to 32-bit.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/thunk] On systems that lack automatic virtual memory hardware, thunks can implement a limited form of virtual memory known as overlays.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/thunk] With overlays, a developer divides a program's code into segments that can be loaded and unloaded independently, and identifies the entry points into each segment.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/thunk] A segment that calls into another segment must do so indirectly via a branch table.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/thunk] When a segment is in memory, its branch table entries jump into the segment.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/thunk] When a segment is unloaded, its entries are replaced with "reload thunks" that can reload it on demand.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/thunk] Similarly, systems that dynamically link modules of a program together at run-time can use thunks to connect the modules.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/thunk] Each module can call the others through a table of thunks that the linker fills in when it loads the module.
[src:lazy-evaluation-theory/thunk] This way the modules can interact without prior knowledge of where they are located in memory.
